<subSubSection id="C36F6539FF91447EEED668EFFD69F88A" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BCA36B2FF91447EEED668EFFD69F88A" blockId="2.[151,1437,1770,1905]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">
<emphasis id="B901EAA0FF91447EEED668EFFEEAF8FE" bold="true" box="[151,276,1770,1796]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFE44B43FF91447EEF5D68EFFE23F8FE" author="Simonsen, T. J." box="[284,477,1770,1796]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" refId="ref13172" refString="Simonsen, T. J. (2018) Splendid Ghost Moths and their Allies, A Revision of Australian Abantiades, Oncopera, Aenetus, Archaeoaenetus and Zelotypia (Hepialidae). In: Monographs on Australian Lepidoptera. Vol. 12. CSIRO Publishing, Melbourne, pp. 1 - 300. https: // doi. org / 10.1071 / 9781486307487" type="book" year="2018">Simonsen (2018)</bibRefCitation>
produced a new diagnosis for the genus, “A patch of elongate scales at the forewing base and the ‘sensory tubercles’ on S2 are both unique and diagnostic for 
<taxonomicName id="4C754D31FF91447EED87690BFBBAF8D2" authorityName="Herrich-Schaffer" authorityYear="1855" box="[966,1092,1806,1832]" class="Insecta" family="Hepialidae" genus="Abantiades" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B901EAA0FF91447EED87690BFBBAF8D2" box="[966,1092,1806,1832]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">Abantiades</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
”. The genus also has hepialine (
<bibRefCitation id="EFE44B43FF91447EEEDE6937FE9EF8B6" author="Dumbleton, L. J." box="[159,352,1842,1868]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" pagination="920 - 981" refId="ref12259" refString="Dumbleton, L. J. (1966) Genitalia, classification, and zoogeography of New Zealand Hepialidae (Lepidoptera). New Zealand Journal of Science, 9 (4), 920 - 981." type="journal article" year="1966">Dumbleton 1966</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE44B43FF91447EEF2A6937FDF4F8B6" author="Dugdale, J. S." box="[363,522,1842,1868]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" pagination="1 - 164" refId="ref12227" refString="Dugdale, J. S. (1994) Hepialidae (Insecta: Lepidoptera). Fauna of New Zealand, Canterbury, New Zealand, 30, 1 - 164." type="journal article" year="1994">Dugdale 1994</bibRefCitation>
) venation, and monopectinate antennae that lack scales on the flagellum (as noted by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE44B43FF91447EEEFB6953FE84F88A" author="Simonsen, T. J." box="[186,378,1878,1904]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" refId="ref13172" refString="Simonsen, T. J. (2018) Splendid Ghost Moths and their Allies, A Revision of Australian Abantiades, Oncopera, Aenetus, Archaeoaenetus and Zelotypia (Hepialidae). In: Monographs on Australian Lepidoptera. Vol. 12. CSIRO Publishing, Melbourne, pp. 1 - 300. https: // doi. org / 10.1071 / 9781486307487" type="book" year="2018">Simonsen (2018)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE44B43FF91447EEFF06952FD75F88A" author="Moore, M. D. &amp; Beaver, E. P. &amp; Velasco-Castrillon, A. &amp; Stevens, M. I." box="[433,651,1878,1905]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" pagination="115 - 141" refId="ref12788" refString="Moore, M. D., Beaver, E. P., Velasco-Castrillon, A. &amp; Stevens, M. I. (2020 a) Four new species of tri-forked Abantiades Herrich- Schaffer (Lepidoptera: Hepialidae) from the &quot; dark obscura clade &quot;. Zootaxa, 4801 (1), 115 - 141. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4801.1.5" type="journal article" year="2020">
Moore 
<emphasis id="B901EAA0FF91447EEC436952FDCAF88A" box="[514,564,1878,1904]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">et al</emphasis>
. 2020a
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
